Preheat the #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Chop the @sweet potato{2} widthways into 1cm thick rounds.

Using a #knife{}, carefully carve eyes and a mouth into each slice to make scary sweet potato faces.

On a lined #baking tray{}, toss with @salt{to taste}, @pepper{to taste} and a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Cook on the top shelf of the oven until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

> TIP: If you aren't into scary stuff, cut the sweet potatoes into wedges and cook as above.

Thinly slice the @tomato{1}.

Mix the @Irish pork mince{250%grams}, @mustard{1%sachet}, @Mexican style spice mix{1%sachet}, @breadcrumbs{1%pack} and @water{2%tbsp} (double for 4p) in a large #bowl{}.
Add a generous pinch of salt and pepper and mix everything together by hand until well combined.
Form the mixture into evenly-sized burgers—1 per person.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat.

> TIP: The burgers will shrink a little as they cook.

Place a pan over medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil.
Once the pan is hot, fry the burgers until cooked through and nicely browned on each side, ~{12-15%minutes} total.
Turn every ~{2-3%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Burgers are cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once cooked, pop the @grated cheese{50%grams} on top of the burgers, pressing it down gently so it stays in place.
Reduce the heat to low, add a splash of water to the pan and cover with a #lid{} or some #tin foil{}.
Allow the cheese melt, ~{2-3%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat.
Meanwhile, pop the @brioche buns{2} into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Spread @aioli{1%sachet} and @ketchup{2%sachets} over the cut side of each bun.
Divide tomato slices between bun bases.
Place a cheesy burger on top.
Close with the bun lid.
Serve with the scary sweet potato faces alongside.